"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 9–11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2kings-9-11.py

Ch 9: Jehu anointed and purges Ahab's house — prophetic anointing pattern (Acts 10:38);
       Jezebel's death fulfills Elijah's word and types the judgment of Babylon (Rev 17–18);
       garment-spreading at Jehu's proclamation shadows the triumphal entry (Matt 21:7–9);
       blood of Naboth avenged types the eschatological avenging of martyrs (Rev 19:2).
Ch 10: Baal worship eliminated — Jehu's temple-clearing shadows Christ's temple cleansing
        (John 2:13–22); but Jehu's partial obedience (v29, 31) contrasts with Christ's
        complete law-keeping (Matt 5:17–20); "nothing of YHWH's word falls to the ground"
        (v10) anticipates Jesus's "not one jot or tittle" (Matt 5:18).
Ch 11: Athaliah's attempted destruction of the messianic line — the most dramatic direct
        threat to the Davidic seed; Joash hidden in the temple types the Christ-child
        preserved in Egypt (Matt 2:13–15); v1 matches Pharaoh's massacre (Exod 1:16)
        and Herod's (Matt 2:16); Jehoiada's covenant renewal (v17) types the new covenant.

Key decisions:
- v13 (garment-spreading): classified as shadow, not direct type — the verbal parallel
  is real but 2 Kgs 9 is not cited in the NT passion accounts
- v1 Athaliah: classified as direct structural type of Matt 2:16 — the pattern of
  destroying "all the royal seed" to prevent the legitimate king from reigning is
  explicitly reproduced in Herod's action
- v12 crown + covenant document: ʿēdût rendered "covenant document" per most commentators
  (Keil, Cogan); the coronation-investiture structure is typologically significant for
  Psalm 2 and Revelation 19
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS2 = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>Elisha commissions an unnamed son of the prophets to anoint Jehu — the third anointing in the Elijah-Elisha cycle (after Elijah anoints Hazael and Elisha, 1 Kgs 19:15-16). The pattern of prophetic anointing anticipates Acts 10:38 where Peter describes Jesus as one &ldquo;anointed by God with the Holy Spirit and with power&rdquo; — both the OT kings and Jesus receive their commissioning through a prophetic/divine anointing before their public mission begins.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The messenger is sent to identify Jehu specifically &ldquo;from among his companions&rdquo; and take him into an inner room for private anointing — a pattern of divine calling that sets one apart from the crowd before public installation. Jesus is similarly identified at his baptism (&ldquo;This is my beloved Son&rdquo;, Matt 3:17) before his public ministry, a private divine commissioning preceding a public mission.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;I anoint you king over Israel&rdquo; (<em>m&acirc;šaḥtîḵā l&eacute;melek</em>) — the anointing formula is spoken over Jehu as YHWH&rsquo;s designated instrument of judgment. The verb <em>m&acirc;šaḥ</em> (H4886) is the root of <em>m&aring;š&icirc;aḥ</em> (Messiah, the Anointed One) — every royal anointing in the OT is a shadow that points toward the ultimate anointed king, Jesus Christ (Luke 4:18, Acts 4:27).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The young prophet runs quickly to Ramoth-gilead on this urgent commission. The brevity of his obedience (&ldquo;so the young prophet went&rdquo;) is a characteristic pattern of prophetic faithfulness — the messenger does not deliberate but acts on the divine word immediately. As a revelation of God: YHWH accomplishes his purposes through faithful messengers who carry his word without adding to or delaying it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jehu is found sitting with the army commanders. The divine commission arrives not in a spectacular context but in the middle of ordinary military routine. This pattern of calling within the ordinary — Moses at a burning bush, Gideon threshing wheat, David keeping sheep — reaches its fullest expression when the eternal Son takes flesh in a Bethlehem stable.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The anointing is performed and the formula spoken: &ldquo;Thus says the LORD, the God of Israel: I anoint you king over the people of the LORD, over Israel.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;the God of Israel&rdquo; grounds the anointing in covenant identity — this is not merely political appointment but divine commissioning on behalf of the covenant people. The same framework applies to Christ, anointed as messianic king over the true Israel (Gal 3:16, 29).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;You shall strike down the house of Ahab your master, so that I may avenge on Jezebel the blood of my servants the prophets.&rdquo; The theme of avenging the blood of the prophets runs through the OT and reaches its climax in the NT. In Matt 23:35 Jesus says all the righteous blood shed will come on that generation; in Rev 19:2 the heavenly host declares that God &ldquo;has avenged the blood of his servants.&rdquo; Jehu&rsquo;s mission is a partial and local enactment of this eschatological justice.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Total elimination of the house of Ahab — &ldquo;every male, slave or free&rdquo; — reflects the totality of divine covenant judgment when patience is exhausted. This reveals God as one who keeps his word of warning as faithfully as his word of promise. The NT presents Jesus as the one in whom both the full weight of judgment and the full scope of mercy meet (Rom 3:25-26; 2 Cor 5:21).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The house of Ahab is to be &ldquo;like the house of Jeroboam son of Nebat and like the house of Baasha son of Ahijah&rdquo; — every dynasty that apostatizes follows the same pattern of divine judgment. The recurring formula reveals a theological principle: persistent rejection of YHWH is finally irreversible. Jesus frames this principle eschatologically: every tree that does not bear fruit is cut down (Matt 7:19; Luke 13:6-9).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jezebel will be eaten by dogs in the plot of Jezreel — the third repetition of Elijah&rsquo;s prophecy (1 Kgs 21:23). The specificity of the prediction and the literalness of its fulfillment (vv35-37) reveal God&rsquo;s word as operative in history with precision. Jesus speaks with the same authority over the future: &ldquo;Not one jot or tittle will pass from the law until all is accomplished&rdquo; (Matt 5:18) — the divine word always executes exactly what it intends.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The other commanders call the prophet a <em>m&eacute;šugg&acirc;</em> — a madman or &ldquo;crazy fellow.&rdquo; Prophetic speech routinely dismissed as madness is a pattern throughout the OT and NT: Jesus&rsquo;s family says &ldquo;he is out of his mind&rdquo; (Mark 3:21), Paul is called mad by Festus (Acts 26:24), and the Spirit&rsquo;s gifts are mistaken for drunkenness (Acts 2:13). The messenger who carries a radical divine word is inevitably misread by those inside conventional power structures.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jehu reveals the prophetic word privately first: &ldquo;This is what he said to me: This is what the LORD says, I anoint you king over Israel.&rdquo; The pattern of private revelation followed by public proclamation is characteristic of prophetic commissions: Elijah privately anoints, then the public action follows. Jesus teaches disciples privately before speaking publicly (Mark 4:34; 9:31), building toward the ultimate public declaration of his kingship.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Each man spreads his cloak under Jehu on the steps and they blow the trumpet proclaiming &ldquo;Jehu is king.&rdquo; This shadow anticipates the triumphal entry into Jerusalem (Matt 21:7-9) where the crowds spread their garments on the road and cry &ldquo;Hosanna to the Son of David&rdquo; — both scenes involve garment-spreading and royal acclamation. The deeper difference is that Jehu&rsquo;s kingship is proclaimed through military coup while Jesus enters as the humble king of Zech 9:9, riding a donkey.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jehu&rsquo;s conspiracy against Joram begins. The word for &ldquo;conspiracy&rdquo; (<em>qāšar</em>, H7194) is the same term used of the plots against David. Jehu is YHWH&rsquo;s instrument of judgment, but the narrative is careful not to idealize him — his method is violent conspiracy. This reveals that God can work through imperfect human instruments (as in Rom 9:17 regarding Pharaoh) without endorsing their methods — a pattern that finds its antithesis in Christ, whose divine mission was accomplished by the perfectly righteous, not through conspiracy.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Joram is recovering from battle wounds in Jezreel. The wounded king in a time of apparent weakness — the narrative detail creates dramatic irony: Joram thinks he is recovering while YHWH&rsquo;s judgment is already in motion. The theme of divine judgment arriving when human defenses are down anticipates the eschatological motif of the Day of the Lord coming &ldquo;like a thief in the night&rdquo; (1 Thess 5:2).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jehu rides furiously toward Jezreel where Joram lies. The urgency of the approach — Jehu driving as if possessed — reveals that YHWH&rsquo;s judgment, once commissioned, moves with irresistible momentum. As a revelation of God&rsquo;s character: the divine word set in motion does not slow or turn aside (Isa 55:11). This contrasts sharply with YHWH&rsquo;s patient delay in the face of repentance (2 Pet 3:9).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The watchman on the tower sees Jehu&rsquo;s company approaching and reports to the king. The watchman motif in prophetic literature (Isa 21:6; Ezek 3:17; 33:7) frames the prophets as lookouts stationed by YHWH to announce approaching judgment. Jehu embodies the approaching judgment here; the watchman announces it. In the NT, John the Baptist plays the watchman role, announcing the one who comes whose sandals he is not worthy to untie (John 1:27).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Joram&rsquo;s first messenger is sent to ask &ldquo;Is all well?&rdquo; (<em>hăš&acirc;lôm</em>) and the messenger defects to Jehu. The Hebrew <em>šālôm</em> used ironically here — Jezebel&rsquo;s harlotries and sorceries have made true peace impossible (v22). The NT locates the only true <em>šālôm</em> in Christ: &ldquo;Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you — not as the world gives&rdquo; (John 14:27). Until the messianic king comes there is no real peace; until he comes there can be no real <em>šālôm</em>.</p>",
    "19": "<p>A second messenger sent, a second defection. The repeated failure of Joram&rsquo;s attempts at communication reveals the futility of seeking peace by diplomatic message when YHWH&rsquo;s judgment is already in motion. The pattern has a Christological counterpart in the parable of the tenants (Matt 21:34-37) where the landowner sends servants one after another and finally his son.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The watchman identifies Jehu by his driving: &ldquo;The driving looks like the driving of Jehu son of Nimshi — he drives furiously.&rdquo; Jehu is identified by his distinctive action before he arrives. The revelation of God through distinctive character before physical presence anticipates the Prologue&rsquo;s logic: the Word was already known by what he was — &ldquo;In the beginning was the Word&rdquo; — before the incarnation made him physically present (John 1:1, 14).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Joram and Ahaziah both ride out to meet Jehu in the plot of Naboth&rsquo;s land. The narrative detail is deliberate — the judgment on Ahab&rsquo;s house is being executed on the very ground from which that judgment was provoked (v25-26). The precision of divine justice — judgment executed at the scene of the crime — has an NT counterpart in Rev 16:6: &ldquo;they shed the blood of saints and prophets, and you have given them blood to drink.&rdquo;</p>",
    "22": "<p>Joram asks &ldquo;Is it peace, Jehu?&rdquo; and Jehu answers: &ldquo;What peace can there be, while your mother Jezebel&rsquo;s whoredoms (<em>z&eacute;nûnîm</em>) and sorceries (<em>k&eacute;šāpîm</em>) are so many?&rdquo; The connection between covenant unfaithfulness and the impossibility of peace is a persistent OT theme (Isa 48:22; 57:21: &ldquo;There is no peace for the wicked&rdquo;). Christ&rsquo;s declaration that he came not to bring false peace but a sword (Matt 10:34) stands in this same prophetic tradition — peace cannot coexist with idolatry.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Joram cries &ldquo;Treachery!&rdquo; (<em>mirm&acirc;</em>) as he flees. The irony is complete — the Omride dynasty itself built its position on the treachery of Zimri against Elah (1 Kgs 16:9-11) and on Jezebel&rsquo;s treacherous manipulation against Naboth. The pattern reveals God&rsquo;s principle of proportional judgment: those who built power through deception experience the same fate (Obad 15: &ldquo;what you have done will be done to you&rdquo;).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Jehu shoots Joram through the heart with an arrow. The execution is swift and certain — YHWH&rsquo;s instrument does not hesitate or miss. As a revelation of God: divine judgment on apostasy, once commissioned, is executed with precision. The NT images of divine judgment — the sharp sword from Christ&rsquo;s mouth (Rev 19:15), the word of God &ldquo;sharper than any two-edged sword&rdquo; (Heb 4:12) — carry this sense of precise, penetrating judgment.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Jehu commands his aide to throw Joram&rsquo;s body into &ldquo;the plot of land belonging to Naboth the Jezreelite&rdquo; — invoking the Elijah prophecy (1 Kgs 21:19). The twenty-year gap between prophecy and fulfillment reveals something about God&rsquo;s justice: it is neither hasty nor forgetful. The NT presents the eschatological judgment as the final settlement of all outstanding accounts: &ldquo;I will repay, says the Lord&rdquo; (Rom 12:19; cf. Heb 10:30).</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;Surely I saw yesterday the blood of Naboth and the blood of his sons — declares the LORD — and I will repay you on this plot&rdquo; — Jehu quotes the prophetic word verbatim. The blood of victims cries out to YHWH (Gen 4:10; Heb 12:24). The theme of God hearing and avenging innocent blood reaches its climax in Rev 6:10 where the martyrs under the altar cry &ldquo;How long before you judge and avenge our blood?&rdquo; and in Rev 19:2 where the vindication is announced.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Ahaziah of Judah is struck down and dies at Megiddo. A Davidic king falls in the purge — the messianic line is struck even as YHWH&rsquo;s judgment falls on the Omrides. This is a dangerous moment for the Davidic covenant. The nearness of the messianic line to destruction at Megiddo (a name associated with eschatological battle in Rev 16:16, Armageddon) reveals how frequently the covenant promise teetered on the edge of human contingency, sustained only by God&rsquo;s faithfulness.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Ahaziah is carried to Jerusalem and buried &ldquo;in his tomb in the city of David.&rdquo; Even in death, the Davidic king is returned to the city of the covenant and the dynastic burial place. The covenant remains operative even over fallen kings — a revelation of God&rsquo;s sustained faithfulness to the Davidic promise despite the unworthiness of its bearers, pointing forward to the one Davidic heir who will be worthy (Rev 22:16).</p>",
    "29": "<p>The regnal synchronism for Ahaziah&rsquo;s accession. These chronological notations, while seemingly administrative, carry theological freight: they anchor the covenant history in real time, in real political succession. The NT does the same in Luke 3:1-2, anchoring the gospel&rsquo;s beginning in the reign of Tiberius Caesar and the high priesthood of Annas and Caiaphas — the divine intervention into history is always precisely situated.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Jezebel hears Jehu is coming, applies eye makeup, and looks down from the window. The verb &ldquo;put on eye makeup&rdquo; (<em>wattāśem</em>) and &ldquo;arranged her hair&rdquo; signal self-presentation before death — Jezebel meets her end as she lived, performing power through appearance. Her adorned face at the window evokes the seductive-queen imagery that becomes, in Rev 17:4, the dress of Babylon the great harlot — &ldquo;dressed in purple and scarlet, and adorned with gold and precious stones.&rdquo;</p>",
    "31": "<p>Jezebel calls Jehu &ldquo;Zimri, murderer of your master.&rdquo; She compares Jehu to the short-lived usurper Zimri who lasted only seven days (1 Kgs 16:15-20). The taunt is an attempt to delegitimize him as a mere assassin. The parallel is ironic: Zimri set fire to the palace and died; Jezebel will be thrown from a window and devoured by dogs. Her words betray no fear — she faces judgment with defiance, which is precisely the posture Revelation assigns to Babylon (Rev 18:7: &ldquo;I sit as queen... I will never mourn&rdquo;).</p>",
    "32": "<p>Jehu looks up and asks &ldquo;Who is on my side?&rdquo; (<em>mî ʾittî</em>). Two or three court officials look down. The rapid defection of Jezebel&rsquo;s own household servants reveals the isolation of the wicked at the moment of judgment — even those closest to her abandon her. The theme of ultimate isolation in judgment contrasts with Christ&rsquo;s promise that he will never abandon those who are his (John 10:28; Heb 13:5).</p>",
    "33": "<p>Jezebel is thrown down, her blood spatters, and Jehu tramples her. The brutal literalness of the fulfillment of Elijah&rsquo;s prophecy reveals YHWH as one who keeps his word to the letter — not metaphorically but historically and physically. The NT presses this even further: the prophetic word concerning Christ was not merely impressionistically fulfilled but with specific, verifiable historical precision (Luke 24:44-46; 1 Cor 15:3-4).</p>",
    "34": "<p>Jehu goes in and eats — a detail that underscores the completeness of his confidence in divine vindication. Then he orders Jezebel buried &ldquo;for she is a king&rsquo;s daughter.&rdquo; The recognition of Jezebel&rsquo;s royal status even in judgment reflects a principle that divine judgment is not contemptuous of the dignity of persons. The NT parallel: even the judgment of Babylon in Rev 18 includes mourning by those who benefited from her commerce.</p>",
    "35": "<p>When the servants go to bury Jezebel, they find only the skull, feet, and palms of her hands. The dogs have consumed her precisely as Elijah prophesied. The completeness of the fulfillment — down to the specific body parts remaining — demonstrates that prophetic precision is not poetic hyperbole but literal anticipation of what YHWH will accomplish. The NT argument for the reliability of OT prophecy (2 Pet 1:19-21) rests on exactly this kind of demonstrated accuracy.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Jehu recognizes the fulfillment: &ldquo;This is the word of the LORD that he spoke through his servant Elijah the Tishbite.&rdquo; The naming of prophet, content, and fulfillment together constitutes a complete prophetic cycle. This reflexive recognition — &ldquo;this is what was spoken&rdquo; — is the pattern the NT authors use repeatedly to identify Jesus&rsquo;s ministry as fulfillment (Matt 1:22; Acts 2:16; 13:27).</p>",
    "37": "<p>&ldquo;The corpse of Jezebel shall be as dung on the surface of the field in the plot of Jezreel, so that no one will be able to say, &lsquo;This is Jezebel.&rsquo;&rdquo; Total obliteration of the wicked — no monument, no recognizable remains, no name perpetuated. This shadow of the final erasure of wickedness anticipates Rev 20:14 (&ldquo;death and Hades were thrown into the lake of fire&rdquo;) and Rev 21:4 (&ldquo;the former things have passed away&rdquo;). Babylon, like Jezebel, is consumed and forgotten.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Ahab had seventy sons in Samaria — a large dynastic house representing the full extent of the Omride power structure. The number seventy has covenantal resonance in the OT: seventy elders with Moses (Exod 24:1), seventy descendants of Jacob entering Egypt (Gen 46:27), seventy nations (Gen 10). The elimination of seventy sons of Ahab is the complete judicial severance of this dynastic line — the Omride covenant of wickedness fully terminated.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jehu&rsquo;s letter challenges Ahab&rsquo;s servants with a test of loyalty — fight for your master&rsquo;s house or submit. The political logic of dynastic succession is invoked. As a revelation of God: YHWH uses the logic of human power structures to accomplish his purposes, drawing out where allegiances truly lie before executing judgment. The NT parallel is the parable of the talents: the judgment moment reveals what was done with what was entrusted (Matt 25:14-30).</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;Select the best and most qualified of your master&rsquo;s sons and set him on his father&rsquo;s throne.&rdquo; Jehu&rsquo;s challenge is not really a genuine offer — it is a provocation designed to reveal that no human protector can stand against YHWH&rsquo;s commissioned judgment. The impossibility of defending the condemned house is a shadow of the impossibility of resisting divine eschatological judgment (Rev 6:17: &ldquo;who can stand?&rdquo;).</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;Two kings could not stand up to him — how are we going to stand?&rdquo; The capitulation of Ahab&rsquo;s servants before they even fight reveals that YHWH&rsquo;s judgment is already operative in the realm of human will. Fear of YHWH&rsquo;s instrument collapses resistance before it begins. This anticipates the eschatological trembling before Christ&rsquo;s judgment seat (Rev 6:15-16; Phil 2:10-11).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The total submission of Ahab&rsquo;s household — palace administrator, city governor, elders, guardians — &ldquo;we are your servants and will do everything you tell us&rdquo;. The complete capitulation of an entire power structure to YHWH&rsquo;s instrument reveals the principle of Prov 21:30: &ldquo;There is no wisdom, no insight, no plan that can succeed against the LORD.&rdquo; The NT applies this to Christ: all authorities are subject to him (Eph 1:21-22; Col 2:15).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jehu&rsquo;s second letter demands: &ldquo;take the heads of your master&rsquo;s sons and come to me.&rdquo; The order is deliberately ambiguous — &ldquo;men who are your master&rsquo;s sons&rdquo; could mean &ldquo;take the leaders (heads) of the house&rdquo; or literally take their severed heads. The servants interpret it in its most lethal sense. The ambiguity may be intentional: Jehu increases the guilt of the Samarian elders even as he uses them as instruments of judgment.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The seventy heads arrive in Jezreel in baskets — a grotesque display of the complete elimination of the Omride dynasty. The seventy sons of Ahab are simultaneously echoes of the seventy nations of Genesis 10 and the seventy elders of Israel; their destruction has a totalizing symbolic weight. Jesus sends out seventy(-two) disciples to announce the kingdom (Luke 10:1) — a redemptive inversion of this eliminative seventy, harvesting rather than destroying.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Jehu orders the heads piled in two heaps at the gate until morning. The public display of judgment is a feature of ancient Near Eastern warfare, but here it serves YHWH&rsquo;s purposes of both demonstrating the fulfillment of prophecy and confronting the city with the reality of divine judgment. The gate — the place of civic life, commerce, and justice — becomes the site of prophetic fulfillment made visible.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jehu publicly acknowledges before the people: &ldquo;I was the one who conspired against my master and killed him — but who killed all these?&rdquo; The rhetorical question diverts accountability toward YHWH: the seventy deaths are not attributable to Jehu but to the prophetic word. This is a rare moment of Jehu&rsquo;s acknowledged theological framing — even human political violence, when it executes divine judgment, belongs to a larger story YHWH is authoring.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;Know, then, that nothing of the word of the LORD concerning the house of Ahab will fall to the ground, for the LORD has done what he spoke through his servant Elijah.&rdquo; The affirmation that God&rsquo;s word is incapable of falling to the ground anticipates Jesus&rsquo;s declaration in Matt 5:18: &ldquo;Not the smallest letter or stroke of a letter will disappear from the Law until everything is accomplished.&rdquo; Both are statements about the ontological reliability of divine speech.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jehu kills everyone remaining of Ahab&rsquo;s house — &ldquo;all his officials, his close associates, and his priests until he left no survivor.&rdquo; The totality of the elimination mirrors the completeness of the original prophetic judgment (1 Kgs 21:21). As a revelation of God: when YHWH pronounces covenant judgment, it is comprehensive — not a partial accounting but a final reckoning. The NT parallel is the completeness of Christ&rsquo;s atoning work: &ldquo;It is finished&rdquo; (John 19:30).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jehu departs toward Samaria, stopping at Beth-eked of the Shepherds. The place name &ldquo;Beth-eked&rdquo; (house of binding/shearing) and &ldquo;the Shepherds&rdquo; evokes shepherd imagery. The encounter that follows (vv13-14) involves relatives of Ahaziah who are bound and killed. As a shadow: the shepherd-and-flock language runs through the OT and into Christ who is both the Good Shepherd (John 10:11) and the one who binds the strong man (Matt 12:29).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Jehu meets forty-two relatives of Ahaziah — they identify themselves as relatives of the Judahite king coming to greet the royal family. The collision between northern judgment (aimed at the house of Ahab) and Davidic relatives who are connected to it through Athaliah&rsquo;s intermarriage (Ahaziah&rsquo;s mother was an Omride) shows how deeply the Davidic line had been compromised by the alliance with Ahab. The danger to the messianic line is not only external but internal.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The forty-two are seized and killed at the pit of Beth-eked. Forty-two is a number with eschatological resonance in the NT: forty-two months of tribulation (Rev 11:2; 13:5). These deaths are part of the collateral destruction that YHWH&rsquo;s judgment on the Omride alliance brings — the Davidic line narrowly escapes total elimination (only through Jehosheba&rsquo;s action in ch11). The nearness of the messianic line to total destruction heightens the theological stakes of ch11.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jehu meets Jehonadab son of Rechab and asks: &ldquo;Is your heart as true to mine as mine is to yours?&rdquo; — <em>hayyēš lᵉbāḇᵉḵā y&acirc;šār</em>. The Rechabites were a group known for strict adherence to traditional Yahwistic simplicity (Jer 35:6-10). Jehonadab&rsquo;s &ldquo;Come with me and see my zeal for the LORD&rdquo; has a shadow of the disciples&rsquo; call: Jesus says &ldquo;Come and see&rdquo; (John 1:39) and &ldquo;Follow me&rdquo; — though Jehu&rsquo;s zeal is for violent purge while Jesus&rsquo;s is for self-giving service.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Come with me and see my zeal (<em>qinʾāh</em>) for the LORD.&rdquo; The word <em>qinʾāh</em> means both zeal and jealousy — Elijah had used it of his own passion for YHWH (&ldquo;I have been very jealous for the LORD,&rdquo; 1 Kgs 19:14). Zeal for the house of God becomes, in the NT, the characteristic of Christ: &ldquo;Zeal for your house will consume me&rdquo; (Ps 69:9 cited in John 2:17). But Christ&rsquo;s zeal expresses itself as sacrificial love rather than as military slaughter.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;According to the word of the LORD spoken to Elijah&rdquo; — the fulfillment formula for the completion of the Ahab oracle. The reliability of the word spoken through Elijah is confirmed through historical execution. The NT uses the same structure to argue for the reliability of OT prophecy concerning Christ: &ldquo;These things happened to fulfill what was spoken through the prophets&rdquo; (Matt 26:56). Both are claims about a God whose word does not fail.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jehu&rsquo;s ruse: &ldquo;Ahab served Baal only a little, but Jehu will serve him much more.&rdquo; Deception deployed as a stratagem against false worship. The ethical tension here is real — the narrator approves the outcome (v28) without explicitly endorsing the means. The deception is a concession to fallen human circumstances rather than a model to imitate. Christ, by contrast, confronted falsehood directly and publicly (John 18:20: &ldquo;I have spoken openly to the world&rdquo;).</p>",
    "19": "<p>All Baal&rsquo;s prophets, worshipers, and priests gathered under false pretenses — &ldquo;let none be absent, for I have a great sacrifice for Baal.&rdquo; The language of sacred assembly (<em>ʿăṣārâ</em>) and sacrifice is inverted: the Baal worshipers are themselves the sacrifice. The inversion of worship language is characteristic of the OT prophetic critique of idolatry. In the NT, Paul declares that those who sacrifice to idols sacrifice to demons (1 Cor 10:20), not to God.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Proclaim a solemn assembly (<em>ʿăṣārâ</em>) for Baal.&rdquo; The assembly gathers under the most sacred category of Israelite liturgical life — a solemn convocation — but in the service of a false god. The defilement of worship forms for idolatrous ends was precisely the sin of Jeroboam (1 Kgs 12:31-33) and the Omrides. Christ cleanses the temple to restore true worship (John 2:16); he does not gather worshipers by deception but calls them by truth (John 4:23-24).</p>",
    "21": "<p>All the worshipers of Baal in Israel gathered in the temple — &ldquo;not one was absent.&rdquo; The completeness of the gathering mirrors the completeness of the subsequent destruction. The full assembly for false worship will become the full assembly for divine judgment. The eschatological counterpart is the final gathering before the throne of judgment (Rev 20:11-13) where nothing is missing and nothing is hidden.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Festive garments distributed to the Baal worshipers before the ceremony — vestments appropriate to the Baal cult. The garment symbolism is significant throughout Scripture: proper garments mark proper status before God (Gen 3:21; Matt 22:11-12). These garments distinguish the Baal worshipers from any YHWH worshipers in the temple — a sorting before the judgment, not unlike the separation of sheep and goats (Matt 25:32).</p>",
    "23": "<p>Jehu commands: &ldquo;Search and make sure there is no servant of the LORD here with you, but only worshipers of Baal.&rdquo; The careful separation of YHWH worshipers before the destruction is a type of divine protection of the righteous within the judgment of the wicked. The same separation logic appears in the Exodus plagues (Exod 8:23 — no flies in Goshen) and in the NT teaching that the Son of Man will separate the wheat from the tares (Matt 13:49).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Eighty guards stationed outside with explicit orders: anyone who lets a worshiper escape will die in his place. The absolute accountability of the guards mirrors the absolute nature of divine judgment — no exemptions, no exceptions for oversight. The NT presents Christ as the one who will render to each person according to what they have done (Rev 22:12; Rom 2:6), with the same completeness.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The moment the burnt offering is complete, Jehu commands: &ldquo;Go in and cut them down.&rdquo; The timing — at the climax of Baal worship — is significant: the idol is powerless to protect its worshipers at the very moment of their devotion. The impotence of idols to save their devotees at the moment of crisis is a prophetic theme (Isa 44:17-18; 46:7). Jesus as the only one who can truly save is the positive counterpart (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "26": "<p>The sacred pillar (<em>maṣṣēb&acirc;</em>) of Baal&rsquo;s house is brought out and burned. The sacred standing stone, representing the deity&rsquo;s presence, is incinerated. As a shadow: the destruction of idolatrous sacred objects is a recurring act of covenant faithfulness in the OT (Deut 7:5; Exod 34:13). In the NT, the ultimate displacement of idols is not their physical destruction but the reality of Christ — the image of the invisible God (Col 1:15) that makes all competing images empty.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The house of Baal is demolished and turned into a latrine. The most contemptuous possible desecration — a site of false worship becomes a site of bodily waste. This radical devaluation of what was falsely called sacred reflects the prophetic insistence on the nothingness of idols (<em>ʾ&eacute;lîlîm</em>, Ps 96:5; 1 Cor 8:4: &ldquo;an idol has no real existence&rdquo;). The transformation from temple to latrine is the most extreme possible expression of prophetic demythologization.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;So Jehu eliminated Baal worship from Israel.&rdquo; This is the high-water mark of Jehu&rsquo;s mission — the express purpose for which he was anointed (1 Kgs 19:17). The elimination of institutional Baal worship is a genuine covenant achievement. As a shadow: the removal of the most explicit idolatry from Israel points toward the complete purification that awaits in the eschatological kingdom — a city where &ldquo;nothing unclean will ever enter&rdquo; (Rev 21:27).</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;However, Jehu did not turn away from the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat, who had led Israel into sin — the golden calves at Bethel and Dan.&rdquo; The adversative &ldquo;however&rdquo; (<em>raQ</em>) is devastating: the greatest reformer of the northern kingdom fails to complete the reformation. Partial obedience is not sufficient. The NT presses this contrast through the Sermon on the Mount: not external conformity but heart-level compliance with God&rsquo;s requirements (Matt 5:20-22). Only Christ fulfills the law completely (Matt 5:17).</p>",
    "30": "<p>YHWH commends Jehu for executing judgment on the house of Ahab and promises his dynasty four generations. The conditional, partial reward reveals YHWH as one who honors partial faithfulness within the covenant — he does not withhold all blessing simply because obedience is incomplete. This reveals the principle of Heb 11&rsquo;s hall of faith: God commends faith even in its imperfect forms, while the &ldquo;something better&rdquo; (Heb 11:40) awaits the complete obedience of Christ.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;Jehu was not careful to walk in the law of the LORD, the God of Israel, with all his heart.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;with all his heart&rdquo; (<em>bᵉḵol lᵉb&acirc;b&ocirc;</em>) is the Deuteronomic standard for covenant faithfulness (Deut 6:5). No northern king ever met it. The failure of every human covenant partner to love YHWH with the whole heart is precisely what necessitates the new covenant: &ldquo;I will put my law within them and write it on their hearts&rdquo; (Jer 31:33) — a covenant whose mediator is Christ (Heb 9:15).</p>",
    "32": "<p>YHWH begins to &ldquo;trim off&rdquo; (<em>q&acirc;ṣar</em>) parts of Israel — Hazael strikes the Transjordanian territory. The loss of land as covenant consequence for incomplete faithfulness is a Deuteronomic principle (Deut 28:25). The stripping away of what was promised when the covenant is only partially kept reveals God as one who does not endorse half-measures. The NT parallel: the branch that does not bear fruit is removed (John 15:2).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The specific territories lost — Gilead, Gad, Reuben, Manasseh, from Aroer to the Wadi Arnon — represent the eastern tribal inheritance across the Jordan. These were given in the conquest (Num 32; Josh 13), now being removed. The contraction of the promised land mirrors the contraction of blessing when covenant faithfulness fails. Eschatologically, the NT inverts this: the faithful inherit &ldquo;the earth&rdquo; (Matt 5:5) and an eternal kingdom that can never be reduced.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The regnal formula: &ldquo;the rest of Jehu&rsquo;s acts, everything he did, and all his achievements, are they not recorded in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?&rdquo; The reference to an annalistic archive places this reign within the historical record. The theological point is that God&rsquo;s covenant purposes operate within, not above, verifiable historical process — a principle the NT gospel authors apply meticulously (Luke 1:1-4; John 19:35; 21:24).</p>",
    "35": "<p>Jehu rests with his ancestors and his son Jehoahaz succeeds him. The dynastic succession continues — YHWH&rsquo;s promise of four generations (v30) begins to unfold. As a revelation of God: he keeps his promises of blessing with the same precision as his promises of judgment. The NT anchor of this principle is the resurrection of Christ — YHWH&rsquo;s most decisive promise kept with historical precision (1 Cor 15:3-4; Acts 2:30-32).</p>",
    "36": "<p>Jehu reigned twenty-eight years. The length of the reign is a marker of divine patience with imperfect obedience — Jehu is not cut short despite his failure to walk fully in the law. The twenty-eight years reflects the principle Paul articulates in Rom 3:25: God passed over prior sins in divine forbearance, not because he ignores them but because the full accounting awaits Christ&rsquo;s atoning work.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>Athaliah seizes power and kills &ldquo;all the royal family&rdquo; (<em>kol-zera&rsquo; hammaml&acirc;ḵâ</em>) — literally &ldquo;all the seed of the kingdom.&rdquo; This is the most direct threat to the Davidic messianic line in the entire OT: a would-be queen-mother attempts to extinguish the seed of David completely. The structure is identical to Pharaoh&rsquo;s command to kill all male Hebrew infants (Exod 1:16) and Herod&rsquo;s massacre of the innocents (Matt 2:16-18) — the pattern of satanic opposition attempting to destroy the covenant seed before it produces the Messiah.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jehosheba, daughter of King Joram and sister of Ahaziah, hides Joash in a bed-chamber. One faithful woman preserves the entire messianic line from annihilation. The structural parallel to Moses&rsquo;s preservation (Exod 2:1-10, one woman saves the deliverer) and to Mary (who carries the messianic seed through unique vulnerability) is striking. In each case, the Davidic/messianic line is preserved through a single act of faithful human agency — revealing that YHWH&rsquo;s covenant purposes often hinge on one person&rsquo;s obedience.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Joash is hidden in the house of the LORD for six years while Athaliah rules. The hidden, preserved king resident in the temple — the true heir of David sheltered within YHWH&rsquo;s own house — is a powerful shadow. The Christ-child is similarly hidden in Egypt while Herod rules (Matt 2:13-15); the six years of Joash&rsquo;s hiddenness and the seventh-year revelation follows a Sabbatical pattern: the true king&rsquo;s hiddenness precedes his public vindication.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;In the seventh year&rdquo; Jehoiada acts — the seventh year as the year of release and restoration (Lev 25:4; Deut 15:1). The covenant appointment of the seventh year as the time of liberation gives Joash&rsquo;s restoration a Jubilee-year quality: the rightful heir restored, the usurper removed, the land returned to its proper condition. Jesus begins his ministry in Galilee proclaiming the Year of Jubilee (Luke 4:18-19, citing Isa 61:1-2) — the ultimate seventh-year liberation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jehoiada&rsquo;s detailed military plan divides the guard into thirds for overlapping coverage. The precise planning to protect the hidden king until the moment of his revelation reflects providential wisdom: YHWH&rsquo;s purposes require human faithfulness and wise preparation. As a theme: the protection of the covenant community around its king is entrusted to faithful human stewardship — the same dynamic in which the church is called to guard the gospel entrusted to it (1 Tim 6:20; 2 Tim 1:14).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Gate of Sur and the gate behind the guards are to be covered. The specificity of the military dispositions grounds this covenant-preserving action in real historical contingency: the messianic line is protected not by miracle alone but through the faithful planning of God&rsquo;s servants. The revelation of God: YHWH&rsquo;s sovereignty works through, not despite, the prudent and faithful action of his people — &ldquo;be wise as serpents and innocent as doves&rdquo; (Matt 10:16).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The two off-duty sections guard the king at the temple. The temple as the site of the hidden king&rsquo;s protection is theologically pointed — the true Davidic heir is sheltered in YHWH&rsquo;s own house. The NT develops the temple theme profoundly: Jesus is himself the true temple (John 2:19-21), the permanent dwelling of God with his people, making the stone structure both his home and his type.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Surround the king on every side, each of you with his weapon in his hand. Put to death anyone who comes within the ranks.&rdquo; The ring of armed protection around the hidden king is an image of covenant fidelity: faithful servants standing ready to die in defense of the rightful ruler. As a shadow: the NT images the church as protected by God&rsquo;s own power (John 10:28-29; 1 Pet 1:5) — YHWH himself is the ultimate guardian of his people and his king.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The commanders carry out exactly what Jehoiada ordered. The obedience is complete and detailed — they did &ldquo;everything that Jehoiada the priest commanded.&rdquo; As a revelation of God: YHWH&rsquo;s purposes are accomplished through complete human faithfulness, not partial or selective compliance. The model of the faithful steward who carries out exactly what was commanded (Matt 25:21; Luke 19:17) is grounded in this kind of covenant obedience.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jehoiada distributes the spears and shields belonging to King David that were stored in the house of the LORD. The Davidic weapons drawn from the temple treasury to defend the Davidic heir is a type of the resurrection of Davidic resources at the moment of messianic restoration. The NT parallel: Christ comes as David&rsquo;s heir who takes up the Davidic inheritance — &ldquo;the key of David&rdquo; (Rev 3:7; Isa 22:22) — and wields it to open what was shut.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The guards form a complete ring around the king from south end to north end of the temple, &ldquo;around the altar and the temple.&rdquo; The arrangement is liturgically and militarily precise — the king stands at the center, altar and temple as the covenantal backdrop. The visual image of a legitimate king at the center of a sacred space under armed protection captures the moment when divine covenant and human kingship converge — the type of Revelation&rsquo;s throne-room scenes (Rev 4-5) where the Lamb is at the center.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jehoiada brings out the king&rsquo;s son, places the crown (<em>n&eacute;zer</em>) on him, and gives him the covenant document (<em>ʿēdût</em>). The double investiture — crown and covenant charter — constitutes the complete royal installation: authority conferred and its obligations stated. The NT coronation of Christ has the same dual structure: authority given (Matt 28:18: &ldquo;all authority in heaven and on earth&rdquo;) and covenant obligations enacted (Heb 8:6: &ldquo;he is the mediator of a better covenant&rdquo;). Psalm 2 frames this coronation in its ultimate form: &ldquo;You are my Son; today I have begotten you.&rdquo;</p>",
    "13": "<p>Athaliah hears the noise and comes into the house of the LORD — the usurper confronts the rightful king at the moment of his public installation. The irony is that she enters the sacred space that has sheltered the king she tried to kill. The confrontation between false authority and true kingship played out within the covenant space anticipates the final confrontation between the beast and the Lamb at the marriage supper of the Lamb (Rev 19:19-20).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Athaliah sees the king standing by the pillar &ldquo;as was the custom&rdquo; — the coronation standing-place, the pillar at which kings were installed (2 Kgs 23:3; 2 Chr 34:31). The trumpets and rejoicing surround him. The usurper sees this and tears her robe: &ldquo;Conspiracy! Conspiracy!&rdquo; As a shadow: the coronation of the rightful king brings joy to the faithful (v20) and ruin to the usurper. The ultimate coronation of Christ is met with similar bifurcation: joy for his people (Rev 19:7) and destruction for his enemies (Rev 19:19-21).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jehoiada orders Athaliah taken outside the temple ranks to be executed — she is not to be killed in the sacred space. The liturgical care for not defiling the temple by blood even in the act of just judgment reveals that divine covenant order is maintained even while enforcing justice. The NT parallel: even in the final judgment, God&rsquo;s holiness and justice are inseparable — the righteous judgment of God (2 Thess 1:5) is also ordered and consistent with his character.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Athaliah is led to the royal palace through the horses&rsquo; gate and executed. The usurper who tried to seize the Davidic throne is removed and the rightful heir installed. As a type: Athaliah is a type of every anti-messianic power that usurps what belongs to Christ — the NT&rsquo;s Antichrist, Babylon the harlot, the false prophet — all of whom are finally eliminated to make way for the reign of the legitimate king (Rev 19:20; 20:10).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Jehoiada makes a covenant between YHWH, the king, and the people that they will be YHWH&rsquo;s people; and between the king and the people. The tripartite covenant — YHWH, king, people — is the Sinai structure renewed under the Davidic monarchy. This covenant renewal is a direct type of the new covenant: &ldquo;I will be their God and they will be my people&rdquo; (Jer 31:33) mediated through the true Davidic king, Jesus (Heb 9:15; Luke 22:20). The covenant document given to Joash (v12) finds its fulfillment in the &ldquo;new covenant in my blood&rdquo; (1 Cor 11:25).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Immediately after the covenant, the people destroy the house of Baal, smash the altars and images, and kill Mattan the priest. Covenant renewal and the destruction of competing worship belong together. The Christological dimension: whenever Christ&rsquo;s lordship is truly acknowledged, competing idols fall (Acts 19:19; 1 Thess 1:9). The destruction of the Baal temple follows the covenant — not before — revealing that true worship cannot coexist with false worship once the covenant is renewed.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jehoiada leads the commanders, the Carites, the guards, and all the people in a procession bringing the king from the temple to the palace through the gate of the guards. The processional movement from sacred space (the temple) to governance space (the palace) enacts the integration of priestly and kingly authority. Jesus is both priest and king (Heb 7:1-2; Rev 19:16) — the Melchizedek typology explicitly names this integration as the achievement of the permanent messianic figure.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;All the people of the land rejoiced, and the city was calm.&rdquo; The establishment of the rightful king produces both joy and peace — the two marks of the messianic age (Isa 9:6-7: &ldquo;Prince of Peace&rdquo;; Zeph 3:14-17: &ldquo;Rejoice greatly&rdquo;). This shadow of eschatological joy finds its NT fulfillment in the marriage supper of the Lamb: &ldquo;Let us rejoice and exult and give him the glory&rdquo; (Rev 19:7) — the joy that follows the definitive installation of the true king.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Joash is seven years old when he becomes king. His extreme youth underscores that the covenant&rsquo;s survival through this crisis depended entirely on YHWH&rsquo;s hidden preservation of a child — not on Joash&rsquo;s strength, wisdom, or political power. The pattern of divine purposes carried through human weakness and youth recurs in the OT (David the youngest, Jeremiah called from the womb) and reaches its summit in the incarnation: God&rsquo;s redemptive purposes entering the world as a helpless infant (Luke 2:12), utterly dependent, vulnerable to Herod — yet preserved to reign forever.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2kings')
    merge_comm(c, KINGS2)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2kings', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in KINGS2.values())
    print(f'2kings mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses for ch 9-11')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
